01805 /**
01806  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_asynclistaddr
01807  *
01808  * ASYNCLISTADDR = Current Asynchronous List Address Register
01809  *
01810  * This 32-bit register contains the address of the next asynchronous queue head to be executed. If the host
01811  * controller is in 64-bit mode (as indicated by a one in 64-bit Addressing Capability field in the
01812  * HCCPARAMS register), then the most significant 32 bits of every control data structure address comes from
01813  * the CTRLDSSEGMENT register (See Section 2.3.5). Bits [4:0] of this register cannot be modified by system
01814  * software and will always return a zero when read. The memory structure referenced by this physical memory
01815  * pointer is assumed to be 32-byte (cache line) aligned.
01816  */
01817 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr {
01818     uint32_t u32;
01819     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s {
01820 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01821     uint32_t lpl                          : 27; /**< Link Pointer Low (LPL). These bits correspond to memory address signals [31:5],
01822                                                          respectively. This field may only reference a Queue Head (QH). */
01823     uint32_t reserved_0_4                 : 5;
01824 #else
01825     uint32_t reserved_0_4                 : 5;
01826     uint32_t lpl                          : 27;
01827 #endif
01828     } s;
01829     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cn61xx;
01830     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cn63xx;
01831     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cn63xxp1;
01832     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cn66xx;
01833     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cn68xx;
01834     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cn68xxp1;
01835     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_asynclistaddr_s cnf71xx;

01841  *
01842  * CONFIGFLAG = Configure Flag Register
01843  * This register is in the auxiliary power well. It is only reset by hardware when the auxiliary power is initially
01844  * applied or in response to a host controller reset.
01845  */
01846 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_configflag {

01851     uint32_t cf                           : 1;  /**< Configure Flag (CF) .Host software sets this bit as the last action in
01852                                                          its process of configuring the Host Controller (see Section 4.1). This bit controls the
01853                                                          default port-routing control logic. Bit values and side-effects are listed below.
01854                                                           0b: Port routing control logic default-routes each port to an implementation
01855                                                               dependent classic host controller.
01856                                                           1b: Port routing control logic default-routes all ports to this host controller. */
01857 #else

01872 /**
01873  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_ctrldssegment
01874  *
01875  * CTRLDSSEGMENT = Control Data Structure Segment Register
01876  *
01877  * This 32-bit register corresponds to the most significant address bits [63:32] for all EHCI data structures. If
01878  * the 64-bit Addressing Capability field in HCCPARAMS is a zero, then this register is not used. Software
01879  * cannot write to it and a read from this register will return zeros.
01880  *
01881  * If the 64-bit Addressing Capability field in HCCPARAMS is a one, then this register is used with the link
01882  * pointers to construct 64-bit addresses to EHCI control data structures. This register is concatenated with the
01883  * link pointer from either the PERIODICLISTBASE, ASYNCLISTADDR, or any control data structure link
01884  * field to construct a 64-bit address.
01885  *
01886  * This register allows the host software to locate all control data structures within the same 4 Gigabyte
01887  * memory segment.
01888  */
01889 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment {
01890     uint32_t u32;
01891     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s {
01892 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01893     uint32_t ctrldsseg                    : 32; /**< Control Data Strucute Semgent Address Bit [63:32] */
01894 #else
01895     uint32_t ctrldsseg                    : 32;
01896 #endif
01897     } s;
01898     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cn61xx;
01899     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cn63xx;
01900     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cn63xxp1;
01901     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cn66xx;
01902     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cn68xx;
01903     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cn68xxp1;
01904     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_s cnf71xx;
01905 };
01906 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment cvmx_uahcx_ehci_ctrldssegment_t;
01907 
01908 /**
01909  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_frindex
01910  *
01911  * FRINDEX = Frame Index Register
01912  * This register is used by the host controller to index into the periodic frame list. The register updates every
01913  * 125 microseconds (once each micro-frame). Bits [N:3] are used to select a particular entry in the Periodic
01914  * Frame List during periodic schedule execution. The number of bits used for the index depends on the size of
01915  * the frame list as set by system software in the Frame List Size field in the USBCMD register.
01916  * This register cannot be written unless the Host Controller is in the Halted state as indicated by the
01917  * HCHalted bit. A write to this register while the Run/Stop bit is set to a one (USBCMD register) produces
01918  * undefined results. Writes to this register also affect the SOF value.
01919  */
01920 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_frindex {
01921     uint32_t u32;
01922     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_frindex_s {
01923 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01924     uint32_t reserved_14_31               : 18;
01925     uint32_t fi                           : 14; /**< Frame Index. The value in this register increments at the end of each time frame (e.g.
01926                                                          micro-frame). Bits [N:3] are used for the Frame List current index. This means that each
01927                                                          location of the frame list is accessed 8 times (frames or micro-frames) before moving to
01928                                                          the next index. The following illustrates values of N based on the value of the Frame List
01929                                                          Size field in the USBCMD register.
01930                                                          USBCMD[Frame List Size] Number Elements N
01931                                                             00b (1024) 12
01932                                                             01b (512) 11
01933                                                             10b (256) 10
01934                                                             11b Reserved */
01935 #else
01936     uint32_t fi                           : 14;

01992                                                          no extended capabilities are implemented. A non-zero value in this register indicates the

01999                                                          significant 3 bits indicates the number of micro-frames a host controller can hold a set of
02000                                                          isochronous data structures (one or more) before flushing the state. When bit [7] is a
02001                                                          one, then host software assumes the host controller may cache an isochronous data
02002                                                          structure for an entire frame. Refer to Section 4.7.2.1 for details on how software uses
02003                                                          this information for scheduling isochronous transfers. */
02004     uint32_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;

02006                                                          bit is set to a one, then the host controller supports the park feature for high-speed
02007                                                          queue heads in the Asynchronous Schedule. The feature can be disabled or enabled
02008                                                          and set to a specific level by using the Asynchronous Schedule Park Mode Enable and
02009                                                          Asynchronous Schedule Park Mode Count fields in the USBCMD register. */
02010     uint32_t pflf                         : 1;  /**< Programmable Frame List Flag. Default = Implementation dependent. If this bit is set
02011                                                          to a zero, then system software must use a frame list length of 1024 elements with this
02012                                                          host controller. The USBCMD register Frame List Size field is a read-only register and
02013                                                          should be set to zero.
02014                                                          If set to a one, then system software can specify and use a smaller frame list and
02015                                                          configure the host controller via the USBCMD register Frame List Size field. The frame
02016                                                          list must always be aligned on a 4K page boundary. This requirement ensures that the
02017                                                          frame list is always physically contiguous. */

02019                                                           this implementation. The value of this field determines whether software should use the
02020                                                           data structures defined in Section 3 (32-bit) or those defined in Appendix B (64-bit).
02021                                                           Values for this field have the following interpretation:
02022                                                          - 0: data structures using 32-bit address memory pointers
02023                                                          - 1: data structures using 64-bit address memory pointers */
02024 #else

02026     uint32_t pflf                         : 1;
02027     uint32_t aspc                         : 1;
02028     uint32_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;

02044 /**
02045  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_hcsparams

02047  * HCSPARAMS = Host Controller Structural Parameters
02048  * This is a set of fields that are structural parameters: Number of downstream ports, etc.
02049  */
02050 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_hcsparams {
02051     uint32_t u32;

02053 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

02055     uint32_t dpn                          : 4;  /**< Debug Port Number. Optional. This register identifies which of the host controller ports
02056                                                          is the debug port. The value is the port number (one-based) of the debug port. A nonzero
02057                                                          value in this field indicates the presence of a debug port. The value in this register
02058                                                          must not be greater than N_PORTS (see below). */

02061                                                          indicator control. When this bit is a one, the port status and control
02062                                                          registers include a read/writeable field for controlling the state of
02063                                                          the port indicator. */
02064     uint32_t n_cc                         : 4;  /**< Number of Companion Controller. This field indicates the number of
02065                                                          companion controllers associated with this USB 2.0 host controller.
02066                                                          A zero in this field indicates there are no companion host controllers.
02067                                                          Port-ownership hand-off is not supported. Only high-speed devices are
02068                                                          supported on the host controller root ports.
02069                                                          A value larger than zero in this field indicates there are companion USB 1.1 host
02070                                                          controller(s). Port-ownership hand-offs are supported. High, Full-and Low-speed
02071                                                          devices are supported on the host controller root ports. */

02073                                                          the number of ports supported per companion host controller. It is used to
02074                                                          indicate the port routing  configuration to system software. */
02075     uint32_t prr                          : 1;  /**< Port Routing Rules. This field indicates the method used by this implementation for
02076                                                          how all ports are mapped to companion controllers. The value of this field has
02077                                                          the following interpretation:
02078                                                          0 The first N_PCC ports are routed to the lowest numbered function
02079                                                            companion host controller, the next N_PCC port are routed to the next
02080                                                            lowest function companion controller, and so on.
02081                                                          1 The port routing is explicitly enumerated by the first N_PORTS elements
02082                                                            of the HCSP-PORTROUTE array. */
02083     uint32_t reserved_5_6                 : 2;
02084     uint32_t ppc                          : 1;  /**< Port Power Control. This field indicates whether the host controller
02085                                                          implementation includes port power control. A one in this bit indicates the ports have
02086                                                          port power switches. A zero in this bit indicates the port do not have port power
02087                                                          switches. The value of this field affects the functionality of the Port Power field
02088                                                          in each port status and control register (see Section 2.3.8). */
02089     uint32_t n_ports                      : 4;  /**< This field specifies the number of physical downstream ports implemented
02090                                                          on this host controller. The value of this field determines how many port registers are
02091                                                          addressable in the Operational Register Space (see Table 2-8). Valid values are in the
02092                                                          range of 1H to FH. A zero in this field is undefined. */
02093 #else

02207                                                           1'b0: 0 by default, the automatic feature is enabled. The Suspend signal is deasserted
02208                                                                 (logic level 1'b1) when run/stop is reset by software, but the hchalted bit is not

02306 /**

02309  * PERIODICLISTBASE = Periodic Frame List Base Address Register
02310  *
02311  * This 32-bit register contains the beginning address of the Periodic Frame List in the system memory. If the
02312  * host controller is in 64-bit mode (as indicated by a one in the 64-bit Addressing Capability field in the
02313  * HCCSPARAMS register), then the most significant 32 bits of every control data structure address comes
02314  * from the CTRLDSSEGMENT register (see Section 2.3.5). System software loads this register prior to
02315  * starting the schedule execution by the Host Controller (see 4.1). The memory structure referenced by this
02316  * physical memory pointer is assumed to be 4-Kbyte aligned. The contents of this register are combined with
02317  * the Frame Index Register (FRINDEX) to enable the Host Controller to step through the Periodic Frame List
02318  * in sequence.
02319  */
02320 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase {

02322     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s {
02323 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02324     uint32_t baddr                        : 20; /**< Base Address (Low). These bits correspond to memory address signals [31:12],respectively. */
02325     uint32_t reserved_0_11                : 12;
02326 #else
02327     uint32_t reserved_0_11                : 12;
02328     uint32_t baddr                        : 20;
02329 #endif
02330     } s;
02331     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s cn61xx;
02332     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s cn63xx;
02333     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s cn63xxp1;
02334     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s cn66xx;
02335     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s cn68xx;

02337     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_periodiclistbase_s cnf71xx;

02341 /**
02342  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_portsc#
02343  *
02344  * PORTSCX = Port X Status and Control Register
02345  * Default: 00002000h (w/PPC set to one); 00003000h (w/PPC set to a zero)
02346  */
02347 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_portscx {
02348     uint32_t u32;
02349     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_portscx_s {

02351     uint32_t reserved_23_31               : 9;

02353                                                          one enables the port to be sensitive to over-current conditions as wake-up events.
02354                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02355     uint32_t wkdscnnt_e                   : 1;  /**< Wake on Disconnect Enable. Writing this bit to a one enables the port to be
02356                                                          sensitive to device disconnects as wake-up events.

02361     uint32_t ptc                          : 4;  /**< Port Test Control. When this field is zero, the port is NOT
02362                                                          operating in a test mode. A non-zero value indicates that it is operating
02363                                                          in test mode and the specific test mode is indicated by the specific value.
02364                                                          The encoding of the test mode bits are (0110b - 1111b are reserved):
02365                                                          Bits Test Mode
02366                                                           0000b Test mode not enabled
02367                                                           0001b Test J_STATE
02368                                                           0010b Test K_STATE
02369                                                           0011b Test SE0_NAK
02370                                                           0100b Test Packet
02371                                                           0101b Test FORCE_ENABLE */
02372     uint32_t pic                          : 2;  /**< Port Indicator Control. Writing to these bits has no effect if the
02373                                                          P_INDICATOR bit in the HCSPARAMS register is a zero. If P_INDICATOR bit is a one,
02374                                                          then the bit encodings are:
02375                                                          Bit Value Meaning
02376                                                           00b Port indicators are off
02377                                                           01b Amber
02378                                                           10b Green
02379                                                           11b Undefined
02380                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02381     uint32_t po                           : 1;  /**< Port Owner.This bit unconditionally goes to a 0b when the
02382                                                          Configured bit in the CONFIGFLAG register makes a 0b to 1b transition. This bit
02383                                                          unconditionally goes to 1b whenever the Configured bit is zero.
02384                                                          System software uses this field to release ownership of the port to a selected host
02385                                                          controller (in the event that the attached device is not a high-speed device). Software
02386                                                          writes a one to this bit when the attached device is not a high-speed device. A one in
02387                                                          this bit means that a companion host controller owns and controls the port. */
02388     uint32_t pp                           : 1;  /**< Port Power. The function of this bit depends on the value of the Port
02389                                                          Power Control (PPC) field in the HCSPARAMS register. The behavior is as follows:
02390                                                          PPC PP    Operation
02391                                                           0b 1b    RO  - Host controller does not have port power control switches.
02392                                                                          Each port is hard-wired to power.
02393                                                           1b 1b/0b R/W - Host controller has port power control switches. This bit
02394                                                                          represents the current setting of the switch (0 = off, 1 = on). When
02395                                                                          power is not available on a port (i.e. PP equals a 0), the port is
02396                                                                          nonfunctional  and will not report attaches, detaches, etc.
02397                                                          When an over-current condition is detected on a powered port and PPC is a one, the PP
02398                                                          bit in each affected port may be transitioned by the host controller from a 1 to 0
02399                                                          (removing power from the port). */
02400     uint32_t lsts                         : 2;  /**< Line Status.These bits reflect the current logical levels of the D+ (bit 11) and D(bit 10)
02401                                                           signal lines. These bits are used for detection of low-speed USB devices prior to
02402                                                           the port reset and enable sequence. This field is valid only when the port enable bit is
02403                                                           zero and the current connect status bit is set to a one.
02404                                                           The encoding of the bits are:
02405                                                            Bits[11:10] USB State   Interpretation
02406                                                            00b         SE0         Not Low-speed device, perform EHCI reset
02407                                                            10b         J-state     Not Low-speed device, perform EHCI reset
02408                                                            01b         K-state     Low-speed device, release ownership of port
02409                                                            11b         Undefined   Not Low-speed device, perform EHCI reset.
02410                                                          This value of this field is undefined if Port Power is zero. */
02411     uint32_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
02412     uint32_t prst                         : 1;  /**< Port Reset.1=Port is in Reset. 0=Port is not in Reset. Default = 0. When
02413                                                          software writes a one to this bit (from a zero), the bus reset sequence as defined in the
02414                                                          USB Specification Revision 2.0 is started. Software writes a zero to this bit to terminate
02415                                                          the bus reset sequence. Software must keep this bit at a one long enough to ensure the
02416                                                          reset sequence, as specified in the USB Specification Revision 2.0, completes. Note:
02417                                                          when software writes this bit to a one, it must also write a zero to the Port Enable bit.
02418                                                          Note that when software writes a zero to this bit there may be a delay before the bit
02419                                                          status changes to a zero. The bit status will not read as a zero until after the reset has
02420                                                          completed. If the port is in high-speed mode after reset is complete, the host controller
02421                                                          will automatically enable this port (e.g. set the Port Enable bit to a one). A host controller
02422                                                          must terminate the reset and stabilize the state of the port within 2 milliseconds of
02423                                                          software transitioning this bit from a one to a zero. For example: if the port detects that
02424                                                          the attached device is high-speed during reset, then the host controller must have the
02425                                                          port in the enabled state within 2ms of software writing this bit to a zero.
02426                                                          The HCHalted bit in the USBSTS register should be a zero before software attempts to
02427                                                          use this bit. The host controller may hold Port Reset asserted to a one when the
02428                                                          HCHalted bit is a one.
02429                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02430     uint32_t spd                          : 1;  /**< Suspend. 1=Port in suspend state. 0=Port not in suspend state. Default = 0. Port
02431                                                          Enabled Bit and Suspend bit of this register define the port states as follows:
02432                                                          Bits [Port Enabled, Suspend]     Port State
02433                                                                       0X                  Disable
02434                                                                       10                  Enable
02435                                                                       11                  Suspend
02436                                                          When in suspend state, downstream propagation of data is blocked on this port, except
02437                                                          for port reset. The blocking occurs at the end of the current transaction, if a transaction
02438                                                          was in progress when this bit was written to 1. In the suspend state, the port is sensitive
02439                                                          to resume detection. Note that the bit status does not change until the port is
02440                                                          suspended and that there may be a delay in suspending a port if there is a transaction
02441                                                          currently in progress on the USB.
02442                                                          A write of zero to this bit is ignored by the host controller. The host controller will
02443                                                          unconditionally set this bit to a zero when:
02444                                                          . Software sets the Force Port Resume bit to a zero (from a one).
02445                                                          . Software sets the Port Reset bit to a one (from a zero).
02446                                                          If host software sets this bit to a one when the port is not enabled (i.e. Port enabled bit is
02447                                                          a zero) the results are undefined.
02448                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02449     uint32_t fpr                          : 1;  /**< Force Port Resume.
02450                                                          1= Resume detected/driven on port. 0=No resume (Kstate)
02451                                                          detected/driven on port. Default = 0. This functionality defined for manipulating
02452                                                          this bit depends on the value of the Suspend bit. For example, if the port is not
02453                                                          suspended (Suspend and Enabled bits are a one) and software transitions this bit to a
02454                                                          one, then the effects on the bus are undefined.
02455                                                          Software sets this bit to a 1 to drive resume signaling. The Host Controller sets this bit to
02456                                                          a 1 if a J-to-K transition is detected while the port is in the Suspend state. When this bit
02457                                                          transitions to a one because a J-to-K transition is detected, the Port Change Detect bit in
02458                                                          the USBSTS register is also set to a one. If software sets this bit to a one, the host
02459                                                          controller must not set the Port Change Detect bit.
02460                                                          Note that when the EHCI controller owns the port, the resume sequence follows the
02461                                                          defined sequence documented in the USB Specification Revision 2.0. The resume
02462                                                          signaling (Full-speed 'K') is driven on the port as long as this bit remains a one. Software
02463                                                          must appropriately time the Resume and set this bit to a zero when the appropriate
02464                                                          amount of time has elapsed. Writing a zero (from one) causes the port to return to high-
02465                                                          speed mode (forcing the bus below the port into a high-speed idle). This bit will remain a
02466                                                          one until the port has switched to the high-speed idle. The host controller must complete
02467                                                          this transition within 2 milliseconds of software setting this bit to a zero.
02468                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02469     uint32_t occ                          : 1;  /**< Over-current Change. 1=This bit gets set to a one when there is a change to Over-current Active.
02470                                                          Software clears this bit by writing a one to this bit position. */
02471     uint32_t oca                          : 1;  /**< Over-current Active. 1=This port currently has an over-current condition. 0=This port does not
02472                                                          have an over-current condition. This bit will automatically transition from a one to a zero when

02474     uint32_t pedc                         : 1;  /**< Port Enable/Disable Change. 1=Port enabled/disabled status has changed.
02475                                                          0=No change. Default = 0. For the root hub, this bit gets set to a one only when a port is
02476                                                                disabled due to the appropriate conditions existing at the EOF2 point (See Chapter 11 of
02477                                                          the USB Specification for the definition of a Port Error). Software clears this bit by writing
02478                                                          a 1 to it.
02479                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02480     uint32_t ped                          : 1;  /**< Port Enabled/Disabled. 1=Enable. 0=Disable. Ports can only be
02481                                                          enabled by the host controller as a part of the reset and enable. Software cannot enable
02482                                                          a port by writing a one to this field. The host controller will only set this bit to a one when
02483                                                          the reset sequence determines that the attached device is a high-speed device.
02484                                                          Ports can be disabled by either a fault condition (disconnect event or other fault
02485                                                          condition) or by host software. Note that the bit status does not change until the port
02486                                                          state actually changes. There may be a delay in disabling or enabling a port due to other
02487                                                          host controller and bus events. See Section 4.2 for full details on port reset and enable.
02488                                                          When the port is disabled (0b) downstream propagation of data is blocked on this port,
02489                                                          except for reset.
02490                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02491     uint32_t csc                          : 1;  /**< Connect Status Change. 1=Change in Current Connect Status. 0=No change. Indicates a change
02492                                                          has occurred in the port's Current Connect Status. The host controller sets this bit for all
02493                                                          changes to the port device connect status, even if system software has not cleared an existing
02494                                                          connect status change. For example, the insertion status changes twice before system software
02495                                                          has cleared the changed condition, hub hardware will be setting an already-set bit
02496                                                          (i.e., the bit will remain set). Software sets this bit to 0 by writing a 1 to it.
02497                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02498     uint32_t ccs                          : 1;  /**< Current Connect Status. 1=Device is present on port. 0=No device is present.
02499                                                          This value reflects the current state of the port, and may not correspond
02500                                                          directly to the event that caused the Connect Status Change bit (Bit 1) to be set.
02501                                                          This field is zero if Port Power is zero. */
02502 #else
02503     uint32_t ccs                          : 1;
02504     uint32_t csc                          : 1;
02505     uint32_t ped                          : 1;
02506     uint32_t pedc                         : 1;
02507     uint32_t oca                          : 1;
02508     uint32_t occ                          : 1;
02509     uint32_t fpr                          : 1;
02510     uint32_t spd                          : 1;
02511     uint32_t prst                         : 1;

02536  *
02537  * USBCMD = USB Command Register
02538  * The Command Register indicates the command to be executed by the serial bus host controller. Writing to the register causes a command to be executed.
02539  */
02540 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbcmd {
02541     uint32_t u32;
02542     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbcmd_s {

02544     uint32_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
02545     uint32_t itc                          : 8;  /**< Interrupt Threshold Control. This field is used by system software
02546                                                          to select the maximum rate at which the host controller will issue interrupts. The only
02547                                                          valid values are defined below. If software writes an invalid value to this register, the
02548                                                          results are undefined. Value Maximum Interrupt Interval
02549                                                            00h Reserved
02550                                                            01h 1 micro-frame
02551                                                            02h 2 micro-frames
02552                                                            04h 4 micro-frames

02563                                                          software to tell the host controller to issue an interrupt the next time it advances
02564                                                          asynchronous schedule. Software must write a 1 to this bit to ring the doorbell.
02565                                                          When the host controller has evicted all appropriate cached schedule state, it sets the
02566                                                          Interrupt on Async Advance status bit in the USBSTS register. If the Interrupt on Async
02567                                                          Advance Enable bit in the USBINTR register is a one then the host controller will assert
02568                                                          an interrupt at the next interrupt threshold. */

02570                                                          controller skips processing the Asynchronous Schedule. Values mean:
02571                                                           - 0: Do not process the Asynchronous Schedule
02572                                                           - 1: Use the ASYNCLISTADDR register to access the Asynchronous Schedule. */
02573     uint32_t ps_en                        : 1;  /**< Periodic Schedule Enable. This bit controls whether the host
02574                                                          controller skips processing the Periodic Schedule. Values mean:
02575                                                             - 0: Do not process the Periodic Schedule
02576                                                             - 1: Use the PERIODICLISTBASE register to access the Periodic Schedule. */
02577     uint32_t fls                          : 2;  /**< Frame List Size. This field is R/W only if Programmable
02578                                                          Frame List Flag in the HCCPARAMS registers is set to a one. This field specifies the
02579                                                          size of the frame list. The size the frame list controls which bits in the Frame Index
02580                                                          Register should be used for the Frame List Current index. Values mean:
02581                                                               00b: 1024 elements (4096 bytes) Default value
02582                                                               01b: 512 elements  (2048 bytes)
02583                                                               10b: 256 elements  (1024 bytes) - for resource-constrained environments
02584                                                               11b: Reserved */
02585     uint32_t hcreset                      : 1;  /**< Host Controller Reset (HCRESET). This control bit is used by software to reset
02586                                                          the host controller. The effects of this on Root Hub registers are similar to a Chip
02587                                                          Hardware Reset. When software writes a one to this bit, the Host Controller resets
02588                                                          its internal pipelines, timers, counters, state machines, etc. to their initial
02589                                                          value. Any transaction currently in progress on USB is immediately terminated.
02590                                                          A USB reset is not driven on downstream ports.
02591                                                          This bit is set to zero by the Host Controller when the reset process is complete. Software can not
02592                                                          terminate the reset process early by writing zero to this register.
02593                                                          Software should not set this bit to a one when the HCHalted bit in the USBSTS register is a zero.
02594                                                          Attempting to reset an activtely running host controller will result in undefined behavior. */
02595     uint32_t rs                           : 1;  /**< Run/Stop (RS).
02596                                                            1=Run. 0=Stop.
02597                                                          When set to a 1, the Host Controller proceeds with execution of the schedule.
02598                                                          The Host Controller continues execution as long as this bit is set to a 1.
02599                                                          When this bit is set to 0, the Host Controller completes the current and any
02600                                                          actively pipelined transactions on the USB and then halts. The Host
02601                                                          Controller must halt within 16 micro-frames after software clears the Run bit. The HC
02602                                                          Halted bit in the status register indicates when the Host Controller has finished its
02603                                                          pending pipelined transactions and has entered the stopped state. Software must not
02604                                                          write a one to this field unless the host controller is in the Halted state (i.e. HCHalted in
02605                                                          the USBSTS register is a one). Doing so will yield undefined results. */
02606 #else
02607     uint32_t rs                           : 1;
02608     uint32_t hcreset                      : 1;
02609     uint32_t fls                          : 2;
02610     uint32_t ps_en                        : 1;
02611     uint32_t as_en                        : 1;
02612     uint32_t iaa_db                       : 1;
02613     uint32_t lhcr                         : 1;
02614     uint32_t aspmc                        : 2;
02615     uint32_t reserved_10_10               : 1;
02616     uint32_t aspm_en                      : 1;
02617     uint32_t reserved_12_15               : 4;
02618     uint32_t itc                          : 8;
02619     uint32_t reserved_24_31               : 8;
02620 #endif
02621     } s;

02632 /**
02633  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_usbintr
02634  *
02635  * USBINTR = USB Interrupt Enable Register
02636  * This register enables and disables reporting of the corresponding interrupt to the software. When a bit is set
02637  * and the corresponding interrupt is active, an interrupt is generated to the host. Interrupt sources that are
02638  * disabled in this register still appear in the USBSTS to allow the software to poll for events.
02639  * Each interrupt enable bit description indicates whether it is dependent on the interrupt threshold mechanism.
02640  * Note: for all enable register bits, 1= Enabled, 0= Disabled
02641  */
02642 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbintr {

02648                                                          Async Advance bit in the USBSTS register is a one, the host controller will issue an
02649                                                          interrupt at the next interrupt threshold. The interrupt is acknowledged by software
02650                                                          clearing the Interrupt on Async Advance bit. */
02651     uint32_t hserr_en                     : 1;  /**< Host System Error Enable When this bit is a one, and the Host System
02652                                                          Error Status bit in the USBSTS register is a one, the host controller will issue an
02653                                                          interrupt. The interrupt is acknowledged by software clearing the Host System Error bit. */
02654     uint32_t flro_en                      : 1;  /**< Frame List Rollover Enable. When this bit is a one, and the Frame List
02655                                                          Rollover bit in the USBSTS register is a one, the host controller will issue an
02656                                                          interrupt. The interrupt is acknowledged by software clearing the Frame List Rollover bit. */
02657     uint32_t pci_en                       : 1;  /**< Port Change Interrupt Enable. When this bit is a one, and the Port Change Detect bit in
02658                                                          the USBSTS register is a one, the host controller will issue an interrupt.
02659                                                          The interrupt is acknowledged by software clearing the Port Change Detect bit. */
02660     uint32_t usberrint_en                 : 1;  /**< USB Error Interrupt Enable. When this bit is a one, and the USBERRINT
02661                                                          bit in the USBSTS register is a one, the host controller will issue an interrupt at the next
02662                                                          interrupt threshold. The interrupt is acknowledged by software clearing the USBERRINT bit. */
02663     uint32_t usbint_en                    : 1;  /**< USB Interrupt Enable. When this bit is a one, and the USBINT bit in the USBSTS register
02664                                                          is a one, the host controller will issue an interrupt at the next interrupt threshold.
02665                                                          The interrupt is acknowledged by software clearing the USBINT bit. */
02666 #else
02667     uint32_t usbint_en                    : 1;
02668     uint32_t usberrint_en                 : 1;
02669     uint32_t pci_en                       : 1;
02670     uint32_t flro_en                      : 1;

02674 #endif
02675     } s;

02686 /**
02687  * cvmx_uahc#_ehci_usbsts
02688  *
02689  * USBSTS = USB Status Register
02690  * This register indicates pending interrupts and various states of the Host Controller. The status resulting from
02691  * a transaction on the serial bus is not indicated in this register. Software sets a bit to 0 in this register by
02692  * writing a 1 to it.
02693  */
02694 union cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts {
02695     uint32_t u32;
02696     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s {
02697 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02698     uint32_t reserved_16_31               : 16;
02699     uint32_t ass                          : 1;  /**< Asynchronous Schedule Status. The bit reports the current real
02700                                                          status of the Asynchronous Schedule. If this bit is a zero then the status of the
02701                                                          Asynchronous Schedule is disabled. If this bit is a one then the status of the
02702                                                          Asynchronous Schedule is enabled. The Host Controller is not required to immediately
02703                                                          disable or enable the Asynchronous Schedule when software transitions the
02704                                                          Asynchronous Schedule Enable bit in the USBCMD register. When this bit and the
02705                                                          Asynchronous Schedule Enable bit are the same value, the Asynchronous Schedule is
02706                                                          either enabled (1) or disabled (0). */
02707     uint32_t pss                          : 1;  /**< Periodic Schedule Status. The bit reports the current real status of
02708                                                          the Periodic Schedule. If this bit is a zero then the status of the Periodic
02709                                                          Schedule is disabled. If this bit is a one then the status of the Periodic Schedule
02710                                                          is enabled. The Host Controller is not required to immediately disable or enable the
02711                                                          Periodic Schedule when software transitions the Periodic Schedule Enable bit in
02712                                                          the USBCMD register. When this bit and the Periodic Schedule Enable bit are the
02713                                                          same value, the Periodic Schedule is either enabled (1) or disabled (0). */
02714     uint32_t reclm                        : 1;  /**< Reclamation.This is a read-only status bit, which is used to detect an
02715                                                          empty asynchronous schedule. */
02716     uint32_t hchtd                        : 1;  /**< HCHalted. This bit is a zero whenever the Run/Stop bit is a one. The
02717                                                          Host Controller sets this bit to one after it has stopped executing as a result of the
02718                                                          Run/Stop bit being set to 0, either by software or by the Host Controller hardware (e.g.
02719                                                          internal error). */
02720     uint32_t reserved_6_11                : 6;
02721     uint32_t ioaa                         : 1;  /**< Interrupt on Async Advance. System software can force the host
02722                                                          controller to issue an interrupt the next time the host controller advances the
02723                                                          asynchronous schedule by writing a one to the Interrupt on Async Advance Doorbell bit
02724                                                          in the USBCMD register. This status bit indicates the assertion of that interrupt source. */
02725     uint32_t hsyserr                      : 1;  /**< Host System Error. The Host Controller sets this bit to 1 when a serious error
02726                                                          occurs during a host system access involving the Host Controller module. */
02727     uint32_t flro                         : 1;  /**< Frame List Rollover. The Host Controller sets this bit to a one when the
02728                                                          Frame List Index rolls over from its maximum value to zero. The exact value at
02729                                                          which the rollover occurs depends on the frame list size. For example, if
02730                                                          the frame list size (as programmed in the Frame List Size field of the USBCMD register)
02731                                                          is 1024, the Frame Index Register rolls over every time FRINDEX[13] toggles. Similarly,
02732                                                          if the size is 512, the Host Controller sets this bit to a one every time FRINDEX[12]
02733                                                          toggles. */
02734     uint32_t pcd                          : 1;  /**< Port Change Detect. The Host Controller sets this bit to a one when any port
02735                                                          for which the Port Owner bit is set to zero (see Section 2.3.9) has a change bit transition
02736                                                          from a zero to a one or a Force Port Resume bit transition from a zero to a one as a
02737                                                          result of a J-K transition detected on a suspended port. This bit will also be set as a
02738                                                          result of the Connect Status Change being set to a one after system software has
02739                                                          relinquished ownership of a connected port by writing a one to a port's Port Owner bit. */
02740     uint32_t usberrint                    : 1;  /**< USB Error Interrupt. The Host Controller sets this bit to 1 when completion of a USB
02741                                                          transaction results in an error condition (e.g., error counter underflow). If the TD on
02742                                                          which the error interrupt occurred also had its IOC bit set, both this bit and USBINT
02743                                                          bit are set. */
02744     uint32_t usbint                       : 1;  /**< USB Interrupt. The Host Controller sets this bit to 1 on the completion of a USB
02745                                                          transaction, which results in the retirement of a Transfer Descriptor that had its
02746                                                          IOC bit set. The Host Controller also sets this bit to 1 when a short packet is
02747                                                          detected (actual number of bytes received was less than the expected number of bytes). */
02748 #else
02749     uint32_t usbint                       : 1;
02750     uint32_t usberrint                    : 1;
02751     uint32_t pcd                          : 1;
02752     uint32_t flro                         : 1;
02753     uint32_t hsyserr                      : 1;
02754     uint32_t ioaa                         : 1;
02755     uint32_t reserved_6_11                : 6;
02756     uint32_t hchtd                        : 1;
02757     uint32_t reclm                        : 1;
02758     uint32_t pss                          : 1;
02759     uint32_t ass                          : 1;
02760     uint32_t reserved_16_31               : 16;
02761 #endif
02762     } s;
02763     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cn61xx;
02764     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cn63xx;
02765     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cn63xxp1;
02766     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cn66xx;
02767     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cn68xx;
02768     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cn68xxp1;
02769     struct cvmx_uahcx_ehci_usbsts_s       cnf71xx;
02770 };

02853 /**
02854  * cvmx_uahc#_gbuserraddr
02855  *
02856  * When the AXI master bus returns error response, the SoC bus error is generated. In the host
02857  * mode, the host_system_err port indicates this condition. In addition, it is also indicated in
02858  * UAHC()_USBSTS[HSE]. Due to the nature of AXI, it is possible that multiple AXI transactions
02859  * are active at a time. The host controller does not keep track of the start address of all
02860  * outstanding transactions. Instead, it keeps track of the start address of the DMA transfer
02861  * associated with all active transactions. It is this address that is reported in
02862  * UAHC()_GBUSERRADDR when a bus error occurs. For example, if the host controller initiates a
02863  * DMA
02864  * transfer to write 1 k of packet data starting at buffer address 0xABCD0000, and this DMA is
02865  * broken up into multiple 256 B bursts on the AXI, then if a bus error occurs on any of these
02866  * associated AXI transfers, UAHC()_GBUSERRADDR reflects the DMA start address of 0xABCD0000
02867  * regardless of which AXI transaction received the error.
02868  *
02869  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
02870  */
02871 union cvmx_uahcx_gbuserraddr {
02872     uint64_t u64;
02873     struct cvmx_uahcx_gbuserraddr_s {
02874 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02875     uint64_t busaddr                      : 64; /**< Bus address. Contains the first bus address that encountered an SoC bus error. It is valid
02876                                                          when the UAHC()_GSTS[BUSERRADDRVLD] = 1. It can only be cleared by resetting the core. */
02877 #else
02878     uint64_t busaddr                      : 64;
02879 #endif
02880     } s;
02881     struct cvmx_uahcx_gbuserraddr_s       cn78xx;
02882     struct cvmx_uahcx_gbuserraddr_s       cn78xxp1;
02883 };
02884 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_gbuserraddr cvmx_uahcx_gbuserraddr_t;

02886 /**
02887  * cvmx_uahc#_gctl
02888  *
02889  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
02890  *
02891  */
02892 union cvmx_uahcx_gctl {
02893     uint32_t u32;
02894     struct cvmx_uahcx_gctl_s {
02895 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02896     uint32_t pwrdnscale                   : 13; /**< Power down scale. The USB3 suspend-clock input replaces pipe3_rx_pclk as a clock source to
02897                                                          a small part of the USB3 core that operates when the SuperSpeed PHY is in its lowest power
02898                                                          (P3) state, and therefore does not provide a clock. This field specifies how many suspend-
02899                                                          clock periods fit into a 16 kHz clock period. When performing the division, round up the
02900                                                          remainder.
02901                                                          For example, when using an 32-bit PHY and 25-MHz suspend clock, PWRDNSCALE = 25000 kHz/16
02902                                                          kHz = 1563 (rounded up).
02903                                                          The minimum suspend-clock frequency is 32 KHz, and maximum suspend-clock frequency is 125
02904                                                          MHz.
02905                                                          The LTSSM uses suspend clock for 12-ms and 100-ms timers during suspend mode. According to
02906                                                          the USB 3.0 specification, the accuracy on these timers is 0% to +50%. 12 ms + 0~+50%
02907                                                          accuracy = 18 ms (Range is 12 ms - 18 ms)
02908                                                          100 ms + 0~+50% accuracy = 150 ms (Range is 100 ms - 150 ms).
02909                                                          The suspend clock accuracy requirement is:
02910                                                          _ (12,000/62.5) * (GCTL[31:19]) * actual suspend_clk_period should be between 12,000 and
02911                                                          18,000
02912                                                          _ (100,000/62.5) * (GCTL[31:19]) * actual suspend_clk_period should be between 100,000 and
02913                                                          150,000
02914                                                          For example, if your suspend_clk frequency varies from 7.5 MHz to 10.5 MHz, then the value
02915                                                          needs to programmed is: power down scale = 10500/16 = 657 (rounded up; and fastest
02916                                                          frequency used). */
02917     uint32_t masterfiltbypass             : 1;  /**< Master filter bypass. Not relevant for Cavium's configuration. */
02918     uint32_t reserved_16_17               : 2;
02919     uint32_t frmscldwn                    : 2;  /**< Frame scale down. Scales down device view of a SOF/USOF/ITP duration.
02920                                                          For SuperSpeed/high-speed mode:
02921                                                          0x0 = Interval is 125 us.
02922                                                          0x1 = Interval is 62.5 us.
02923                                                          0x2 = Interval is 31.25 us.
02924                                                          0x3 = Interval is 15.625 us.
02925                                                          For full speed mode, the scale down value is multiplied by 8. */
02926     uint32_t prtcapdir                    : 2;  /**< Port capability direction. Always keep set to 0x1. */
02927     uint32_t coresoftreset                : 1;  /**< Core soft reset: 1 = soft reset to core, 0 = no soft reset.
02928                                                          Clears the interrupts and all the UAHC()_* CSRs except the
02929                                                          following registers: UAHC()_GCTL, UAHC()_GUCTL, UAHC()_GSTS,
02930                                                          UAHC()_GRLSID, UAHC()_GGPIO, UAHC()_GUID, UAHC()_GUSB2PHYCFG(),
02931                                                          UAHC()_GUSB3PIPECTL().
02932                                                          When you reset PHYs (using UAHC()_GUSB2PHYCFG() or UAHC()_GUSB3PIPECTL()), you must keep
02933                                                          the
02934                                                          core in reset state until PHY clocks are stable. This controls the bus, RAM, and MAC
02935                                                          domain resets. */
02936     uint32_t sofitpsync                   : 1;  /**< Synchronize ITP to reference clock. In host mode, if this bit is set to:
02937                                                          0 = The core keeps the UTMI/ULPI PHY on the first port in non-suspended state whenever
02938                                                          there is a SuperSpeed port that is not in Rx.Detect, SS.Disable, and U3 state.
02939                                                          1 = The core keeps the UTMI/ULPI PHY on the first port in non-suspended state whenever the
02940                                                          other non-SuperSpeed ports are not in suspended state.
02941                                                          This feature is useful because it saves power by suspending UTMI/ULPI when SuperSpeed only
02942                                                          is active and it helps resolve when the PHY does not transmit a host resume unless it is
02943                                                          placed in suspend state.
02944                                                          UAHC()_GUSB2PHYCFG()[SUSPHY] eventually decides to put the UTMI/ULPI PHY in to suspend
02945                                                          state. In addition, when this bit is set to 1, the core generates ITP off of the REF_CLK-
02946                                                          based counter. Otherwise, ITP and SOF are generated off of UTMI/ULPI_CLK[0] based counter.
02947                                                          To program the reference clock period inside the core, refer to UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER].
02948                                                          If you do not plan to ever use this feature or the UAHC()_GFLADJ[GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL]
02949                                                          feature, the minimum frequency for the ref_clk can be as low as 32 KHz. You can connect
02950                                                          the
02951                                                          SUSPEND_CLK (as low as 32 KHz) to REF_CLK.
02952                                                          If you plan to enable hardware-based LPM (PORTPMSC[HLE] = 1), this feature cannot be used.
02953                                                          Turn off this feature by setting this bit to zero and use the
02954                                                          UAHC()_GFLADJ[GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] feature.
02955                                                          If you set this bit to 1, the UAHC()_GUSB2PHYCFG() [U2_FREECLK_EXISTS] bit must be set to
02956                                                          0. */
02957     uint32_t u1u2timerscale               : 1;  /**< Disable U1/U2 timer scaledown. If set to 1, along with SCALEDOWN = 0x1, disables the scale
02958                                                          down of U1/U2 inactive timer values.
02959                                                          This is for simulation mode only. */
02960     uint32_t debugattach                  : 1;  /**< Debug attach. When this bit is set:
02961                                                          * SuperSpeed link proceeds directly to the polling-link state (UAHC()_DCTL[RS] = 1)
02962                                                          without checking remote termination.
02963                                                          * Link LFPS polling timeout is infinite.
02964                                                          * Polling timeout during TS1 is infinite (in case link is waiting for TXEQ to finish). */
02965     uint32_t ramclksel                    : 2;  /**< RAM clock select. Always keep set to 0x0. */
02966     uint32_t scaledown                    : 2;  /**< Scale-down mode. When scale-down mode is enabled for simulation, the core uses scaled-down
02967                                                          timing values, resulting in faster simulations. When scale-down mode is disabled, actual
02968                                                          timing values are used. This is required for hardware operation.
02969                                                          High-speed/full-speed/low-speed modes:
02970                                                          0x0 = Disables all scale-downs. Actual timing values are used.
02971                                                          0x1 = Enables scale-down of all timing values. These include:
02972                                                          * Speed enumeration.
02973                                                          * HNP/SRP.
02974                                                          * Suspend and resume.
02975                                                          0x2 = N/A.
02976                                                          0x3 = Enables bits <0> and <1> scale-down timing values.
02977                                                          SuperSpeed mode:
02978                                                          0x0 = Disables all scale-downs. Actual timing values are used.
02979                                                          0x1 = Enables scaled down SuperSpeed timing and repeat values including:
02980                                                          * Number of TxEq training sequences reduce to eight.
02981                                                          * LFPS polling burst time reduce to 100 ns.
02982                                                          * LFPS warm reset receive reduce to 30 us. */
02983     uint32_t disscramble                  : 1;  /**< Disable scrambling. Transmit request to link partner on next transition to recovery or polling. */
02984     uint32_t u2exit_lfps                  : 1;  /**< LFPS U2 exit.
02985                                                          0 = The link treats 248 ns LFPS as a valid U2 exit.
02986                                                          1 = The link waits for 8 us of LFPS before it detects a valid U2 exit.
02987                                                          This bit is added to improve interoperability with a third party host controller. This
02988                                                          host controller in U2 state while performing receiver detection generates an LFPS glitch
02989                                                          of about 4s duration. This causes the device to exit from U2 state because the LFPS filter
02990                                                          value is 248 ns. With the new functionality enabled, the device can stay in U2 while
02991                                                          ignoring this glitch from the host controller. */
02992     uint32_t reserved_1_1                 : 1;
02993     uint32_t dsblclkgtng                  : 1;  /**< Disable clock gating. When set to 1 and the core is in low power mode, internal clock
02994                                                          gating is disabled, which means the clocks are always running. This bit can be set to 1
02995                                                          after power-up reset. */
02996 #else
02997     uint32_t dsblclkgtng                  : 1;
02998     uint32_t reserved_1_1                 : 1;
02999     uint32_t u2exit_lfps                  : 1;
03000     uint32_t disscramble                  : 1;
03001     uint32_t scaledown                    : 2;
03002     uint32_t ramclksel                    : 2;
03003     uint32_t debugattach                  : 1;
03004     uint32_t u1u2timerscale               : 1;
03005     uint32_t sofitpsync                   : 1;
03006     uint32_t coresoftreset                : 1;
03007     uint32_t prtcapdir                    : 2;
03008     uint32_t frmscldwn                    : 2;
03009     uint32_t reserved_16_17               : 2;
03010     uint32_t masterfiltbypass             : 1;
03011     uint32_t pwrdnscale                   : 13;
03012 #endif
03013     } s;
03014     struct cvmx_uahcx_gctl_s              cn78xx;
03015     struct cvmx_uahcx_gctl_s              cn78xxp1;
03016 };
