03241 /**
03242  * cvmx_uahc#_gdmahlratio
03243  *
03244  * This register specifies the relative priority of the SuperSpeed FIFOs with respect to the
03245  * high-speed/full-speed/low-speed FIFOs. The DMA arbiter prioritizes the high-speed/full-speed
03246  * /low-speed round-robin arbiter group every DMA high-low priority ratio grants as indicated in
03247  * the register separately for TX and RX.
03248  *
03249  * To illustrate, consider that all FIFOs are requesting access simultaneously, and the ratio is
03250  * 4. SuperSpeed gets priority for four packets, high-speed/full-speed/low-speed gets priority
03251  * for one packet, SuperSpeed gets priority for four packets, high-speed/full-speed/low-speed
03252  * gets priority for one packet, and so on.
03253  *
03254  * If FIFOs from both speed groups are not requesting access simultaneously then:
03255  * * If SuperSpeed got grants four out of the last four times, then high-speed/full-speed/
03256  * low-speed get the priority on any future request.
03257  * * If high-speed/full-speed/low-speed got the grant last time, SuperSpeed gets the priority on
03258  * the next request.
03259  *
03260  * If there is a valid request on either SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed, a grant
03261  * is always awarded; there is no idle.
03262  *
03263  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03264  */
03265 union cvmx_uahcx_gdmahlratio {
03266     uint32_t u32;
03267     struct cvmx_uahcx_gdmahlratio_s {
03268 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03269     uint32_t reserved_13_31               : 19;
03270     uint32_t rx_ratio                     : 5;  /**< Speed ratio for RX arbitration. */
03271     uint32_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
03272     uint32_t tx_ratio                     : 5;  /**< Speed ratio for TX arbitration. */
03273 #else
03274     uint32_t tx_ratio                     : 5;
03275     uint32_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
03276     uint32_t rx_ratio                     : 5;
03277     uint32_t reserved_13_31               : 19;
03278 #endif
03279     } s;
03280     struct cvmx_uahcx_gdmahlratio_s       cn78xx;
03281     struct cvmx_uahcx_gdmahlratio_s       cn78xxp1;
03282 };
03283 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_gdmahlratio cvmx_uahcx_gdmahlratio_t;
03284 
03285 /**
03286  * cvmx_uahc#_gfladj
03287  *
03288  * This register provides options for the software to control the core behavior with respect to
03289  * SOF (start of frame) and ITP (isochronous timestamp packet) timers and frame timer
03290  * functionality. It provides the option to override the sideband signal fladj_30mhz_reg. In
03291  * addition, it enables running SOF or ITP frame timer counters completely off of the REF_CLK.
03292  * This facilitates hardware LPM in host mode with the SOF or ITP counters being run off of the
03293  * REF_CLK signal.
03294  *
03295  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03296  */
03297 union cvmx_uahcx_gfladj {
03298     uint32_t u32;
03299     struct cvmx_uahcx_gfladj_s {
03300 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03301     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhzdecr_pls1 : 1; /**< This field indicates that the decrement value that the controller applies for each REF_CLK
03302                                                          must be GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR and GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR +1 alternatively on each
03303                                                          REF_CLK. Set this bit to 1 only if [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] is set to 1 and the fractional
03304                                                          component of 240/ref_frequency is greater than or equal to 0.5.
03305                                                          Example:
03306                                                          If the REF_CLK is 19.2 MHz then:
03307                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 52.
03308                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = (240/19.2) = 12.5.
03309                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZDECR_PLS1] = 1.
03310                                                          If the REF_CLK is 24 MHz then:
03311                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 41.
03312                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = (240/24) = 10.
03313                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZDECR_PLS1] = 0. */
03314     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhz_decr    : 7;  /**< This field indicates the decrement value that the controller applies for each REF_CLK in
03315                                                          order to derive a frame timer in terms of a 240-MHz clock. This field must be programmed
03316                                                          to a nonzero value only if [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] is set to 1.
03317                                                          The value is derived as follows:
03318                                                          _ [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/ref_clk_frequency
03319                                                          Examples:
03320                                                          If the REF_CLK is 24 MHz then:
03321                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 41.
03322                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/24 = 10.
03323                                                          If the REF_CLK is 48 MHz then:
03324                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 20.
03325                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/48 = 5.
03326                                                          If the REF_CLK is 17 MHz then:
03327                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 58.
03328                                                          * [GFLADJ_REFCLK_240MHZ_DECR] = 240/17 = 14. */
03329     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_lpm_sel        : 1;  /**< This bit enables the functionality of running SOF/ITP counters on the REF_CLK.
03330                                                          This bit must not be set to 1 if UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1. Similarly, if
03331                                                          GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL = 1, UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] must not be set to 1.
03332                                                          When GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL = 1 the overloading of the suspend control of the USB 2.0 first
03333                                                          port PHY (UTMI) with USB 3.0 port states is removed. Note that the REF_CLK frequencies
03334                                                          supported in this mode are 16/17/19.2/20/24/39.7/40 MHz. */
03335     uint32_t reserved_22_22               : 1;
03336     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_fladj          : 14; /**< This field indicates the frame length adjustment to be applied when SOF/ITP counter is
03337                                                          running off of the REF_CLK. This register value is used to adjust:.
03338                                                          * ITP interval when UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1
03339                                                          * both SOF and ITP interval when [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1.
03340                                                          This field must be programmed to a nonzero value only if [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1 or
03341                                                          UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1.
03342                                                          The value is derived as below:
03343                                                          _ FLADJ_REF_CLK_FLADJ = ((125000/ref_clk_period_integer) - (125000/ref_clk_period)) *
03344                                                          ref_clk_period
03345                                                          where,
03346                                                          * the ref_clk_period_integer is the integer value of the REF_CLK period got by truncating
03347                                                          the decimal (fractional) value that is programmed in UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER].
03348                                                          * the ref_clk_period is the REF_CLK period including the fractional value.
03349                                                          Examples:
03350                                                          If the REF_CLK is 24 MHz then:
03351                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 41.
03352                                                          * GLADJ_REFCLK_FLADJ = ((125000/41) -
03353                                                          (125000/41.6666)) * 41.6666 = 2032 (ignoring the fractional value).
03354                                                          If the REF_CLK is 48 MHz then:
03355                                                          * UAHC()_GUCTL[REFCLKPER] = 20.
03356                                                          * GLADJ_REFCLK_FLADJ = ((125000/20) -
03357                                                          (125000/20.8333)) * 20.8333 = 5208 (ignoring the fractional value). */
03358     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz_reg_sel         : 1;  /**< This field selects whether to use the input signal fladj_30mhz_reg or the [GFLADJ_30MHZ]
03359                                                          to
03360                                                          adjust the frame length for the SOF/ITP. When this bit is set to, 1, the controller uses
03361                                                          [GFLADJ_30MHZ] value 0x0, the controller uses the input signal fladj_30mhz_reg value. */
03362     uint32_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
03363     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz                 : 6;  /**< This field indicates the value that is used for frame length adjustment instead of
03364                                                          considering from the sideband input signal fladj_30mhz_reg. This enables post-silicon
03365                                                          frame length adjustment in case the input signal fladj_30mhz_reg is connected to a wrong
03366                                                          value or is not valid. The controller uses this value if [GFLADJ_30MHZ_REG_SEL] = 1 and
03367                                                          the
03368                                                          SOF/ITP counters are running off of UTMI(ULPI) clock ([GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 0 and
03369                                                          UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] is 1 or 0). For details on how to set this value, refer to
03370                                                          section 5.2.4 Frame Length Adjustment Register (FLADJ) of the xHCI Specification. */
03371 #else
03372     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz                 : 6;
03373     uint32_t reserved_6_6                 : 1;
03374     uint32_t gfladj_30mhz_reg_sel         : 1;
03375     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_fladj          : 14;
03376     uint32_t reserved_22_22               : 1;
03377     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_lpm_sel        : 1;
03378     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhz_decr    : 7;
03379     uint32_t gfladj_refclk_240mhzdecr_pls1 : 1;
03380 #endif
03381     } s;
03382     struct cvmx_uahcx_gfladj_s            cn78xx;
03383     struct cvmx_uahcx_gfladj_s            cn78xxp1;
03384 };
03385 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_gfladj cvmx_uahcx_gfladj_t;

03848 /**
03849  * cvmx_uahc#_grxfifoprihst
03850  *
03851  * This register specifies the relative DMA priority level among the host RXFIFOs (one per USB
03852  * bus instance) within the associated speed group (SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed
03853  * /low-speed). When multiple RXFIFOs compete for DMA service at a given time, the RXDMA arbiter
03854  * grants access on a packet-basis in the following manner:
03855  *
03856  * Among the FIFOs in the same speed group (SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed):
03857  * * High-priority RXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration.
03858  * * Low-priority RXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration only after high-
03859  * priority
03860  * RXFIFOs have no further processing to do (i.e., either the RXQs are empty or the corresponding
03861  * RXFIFOs do not have the required data).
03862  *
03863  * The RX DMA arbiter prioritizes the SuperSpeed group or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed group
03864  * according to the ratio programmed in
03865  * UAHC()_GDMAHLRATIO.
03866  *
03867  * For scatter-gather packets, the arbiter grants successive DMA requests to the same FIFO until
03868  * the entire packet is completed. The register size corresponds to the number of configured USB
03869  * bus instances; for example, in the default configuration, there are 3 USB bus instances (1
03870  * SuperSpeed, 1 high-speed, and 1 full-speed/low-speed).
03871  *
03872  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03873  */
03874 union cvmx_uahcx_grxfifoprihst {
03875     uint32_t u32;
03876     struct cvmx_uahcx_grxfifoprihst_s {
03877 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03878     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
03879     uint32_t rx_priority                  : 3;  /**< Each register bit[n] controls the priority (1 = high, 0 = low) of RXFIFO[n] within a speed group. */
03880 #else
03881     uint32_t rx_priority                  : 3;
03882     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
03883 #endif
03884     } s;
03885     struct cvmx_uahcx_grxfifoprihst_s     cn78xx;
03886     struct cvmx_uahcx_grxfifoprihst_s     cn78xxp1;
03887 };
03888 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_grxfifoprihst cvmx_uahcx_grxfifoprihst_t;

03894  * below. It is recommended that software use the default value. In Host mode, per-port registers
03895  * are implemented. One register per FIFO.
03896  *
03897  * Reset values = 0:[0x0000_0084] 1:[0x0084_0104] 2:[0x0188_0180].
03898  *
03899  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03900  */
03901 union cvmx_uahcx_grxfifosizx {

03904 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03905     uint32_t rxfstaddr                    : 16; /**< RxFIFOn RAM start address. This field contains the memory start address for RxFIFOn. The
03906                                                          reset value is derived from configuration parameters. */
03907     uint32_t rxfdep                       : 16; /**< RxFIFOn depth. This value is in terms of RX RAM Data width.
03908                                                          minimum value = 0x20, maximum value = 0x4000. */
03909 #else

03911     uint32_t rxfstaddr                    : 16;
03912 #endif
03913     } s;

03918 
03919 /**
03920  * cvmx_uahc#_grxthrcfg
03921  *
03922  * In a normal case, an RX burst starts as soon as 1-packet space is available. This works well
03923  * as long as the system bus is faster than the USB3.0 bus (a 1024-bytes packet takes ~2.2 us on
03924  * the USB bus in SuperSpeed mode). If the system bus latency is larger than 2.2 us to access a
03925  * 1024-byte packet, then starting a burst on 1-packet condition leads to an early abort of the
03926  * burst causing unnecessary performance reduction. This register allows the configuration of
03927  * threshold and burst size control. This feature is enabled by USBRXPKTCNTSEL.
03928  *
03929  * Receive Path:
03930  * * The RX threshold is controlled by USBRXPKTCNT and the RX burst size is controlled by
03931  * USBMAXRXBURSTSIZE.
03932  * * Selecting optimal RX FIFO size, RX threshold, and RX burst size avoids RX burst aborts due
03933  * to overrun if the system bus is slower than USB. Once in a while overrun is OK, and there is
03934  * no functional issue.
03935  * * Some devices do not support terminating ACK retry. With these devices, host cannot set ACK=0
03936  * and Retry=0 and do retry later and you have to retry immediately. For such devices, minimize
03937  * retry due to underrun. Setting threshold and burst size guarantees this.
03938  * A larger RX threshold affects the performance since the scheduler is idle during this time.
03939  *
03940  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03941  */
03942 union cvmx_uahcx_grxthrcfg {
03943     uint32_t u32;
03944     struct cvmx_uahcx_grxthrcfg_s {
03945 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03946     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
03947     uint32_t usbrxpktcntsel               : 1;  /**< USB receive-packet-count enable. Enables/disables the USB reception multipacket
03948                                                          thresholding:
03949                                                          0 = the core can only start reception on the USB when the RX FIFO has space for at least
03950                                                          one packet.
03951                                                          1 = the core can only start reception on the USB when the RX FIFO has space for at least
03952                                                          USBRXPKTCNT amount of packets.
03953                                                          This mode is only used for SuperSpeed. */
03954     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
03955     uint32_t usbrxpktcnt                  : 4;  /**< USB receive-packet count. In host-mode, specifies space (in number of packets) that must
03956                                                          be available in the RX FIFO before the core can start the corresponding USB RX transaction
03957                                                          (burst).
03958                                                          This field is only valid when [USBRXPKTCNTSEL] = 1. The valid values are from 0x1 to 0xF.
03959                                                          This field must be <= [USBMAXRXBURSTSIZE]. */
03960     uint32_t usbmaxrxburstsize            : 5;  /**< USB maximum receive-burst size. In host-mode, specifies the maximum bulk IN burst the core
03961                                                          should do. When the system bus is slower than the USB, RX FIFO can overrun during a long
03962                                                          burst.
03963                                                          Program a smaller value to this field to limit the RX burst size that the core can do. It
03964                                                          only applies to SuperSpeed Bulk, Isochronous, and Interrupt IN endpoints in the host mode.
03965                                                          This field is only valid when [USBRXPKTCNTSEL] = 1. The valid values are from 0x1 to 0x10. */
03966     uint32_t reserved_0_18                : 19;
03967 #else
03968     uint32_t reserved_0_18                : 19;
03969     uint32_t usbmaxrxburstsize            : 5;
03970     uint32_t usbrxpktcnt                  : 4;
03971     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
03972     uint32_t usbrxpktcntsel               : 1;
03973     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
03974 #endif
03975     } s;
03976     struct cvmx_uahcx_grxthrcfg_s         cn78xx;
03977     struct cvmx_uahcx_grxthrcfg_s         cn78xxp1;
03978 };
03979 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_grxthrcfg cvmx_uahcx_grxthrcfg_t;
03980 
03981 /**
03982  * cvmx_uahc#_gsbuscfg0
03983  *
03984  * This register can be used to configure the core after power-on or a change in mode of
03985  * operation. This register mainly contains AXI system-related configuration parameters. Do not
03986  * change this register after the initial programming. The application must program this register
03987  * before starting any transactions on AXI. When [INCRBRSTENA] is enabled, it has the highest
03988  * priority over other burst lengths. The core always performs the largest burst when enabled.
03989  *
03990  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
03991  */
03992 union cvmx_uahcx_gsbuscfg0 {
03993     uint32_t u32;
03994     struct cvmx_uahcx_gsbuscfg0_s {
03995 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03996     uint32_t datrdreqinfo                 : 4;  /**< AXI-cache for data-read operations. Always set to 0x0. */

04016                                                          If disabled, the AXI master will use only the burst lengths
04017                                                          1, 4, 8, 16 (assuming the INCR*BRSTENA are set to their reset values).
04018                                                          If enabled, the AXI master uses any length less than or equal to the largest-enabled burst
04019                                                          length based on the INCR*BRSTENA fields. */

04033     uint32_t deswrreqinfo                 : 4;
04034     uint32_t datwrreqinfo                 : 4;
04035     uint32_t desrdreqinfo                 : 4;

04037 #endif

04125 /**
04126  * cvmx_uahc#_gtxfifoprihst
04127  *
04128  * This register specifies the relative DMA priority level among the host TXFIFOs (one per USB
04129  * bus instance) within the associated speed group (SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed
04130  * /low-speed). When multiple TXFIFOs compete for DMA service at a given time, the TXDMA arbiter
04131  * grants access on a packet-basis in the following manner:
04132  *
04133  * Among the FIFOs in the same speed group (SuperSpeed or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed):
04134  *
04135  * * High-priority TXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration.
04136  * * Low-priority TXFIFOs are granted access using round-robin arbitration only after high-
04137  * priority
04138  * TXFIFOs have no further processing to do (i.e., either the TXQs are empty or the corresponding
04139  * TXFIFOs do not have the required data).
04140  *
04141  * The TX DMA arbiter prioritizes the SuperSpeed group or high-speed/full-speed/low-speed group
04142  * according to the ratio programmed in
04143  * UAHC()_GDMAHLRATIO.
04144  *
04145  * For scatter-gather packets, the arbiter grants successive DMA requests to the same FIFO until
04146  * the entire packet is completed. The register size corresponds to the number of configured USB
04147  * bus instances; for example, in the default configuration, there are 3 USB bus instances (1
04148  * SuperSpeed, 1 high-speed, and 1 full-speed/low-speed).
04149  *
04150  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04151  */
04152 union cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifoprihst {
04153     uint32_t u32;
04154     struct cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifoprihst_s {
04155 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04156     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
04157     uint32_t tx_priority                  : 3;  /**< Each register bit n controls the priority (1: high, 0: low) of TX FIFO<n> within a speed
04158                                                          group. */
04159 #else
04160     uint32_t tx_priority                  : 3;
04161     uint32_t reserved_3_31                : 29;
04162 #endif
04163     } s;
04164     struct cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifoprihst_s     cn78xx;
04165     struct cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifoprihst_s     cn78xxp1;
04166 };
04167 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifoprihst cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifoprihst_t;

04172  * This register holds the internal RAM start address/depth of each TxFIFO implemented. Unless
04173  * packet size/buffer size for each endpoint is different and application-specific, it is
04174  * recommended that the software use the default value. One register per FIFO. One register per
04175  * FIFO.
04176  *
04177  * Reset values = 0:[0x0000_0082] 1:[0x0082_0103] 2:[0x0185_0205].
04178  *
04179  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04180  */
04181 union cvmx_uahcx_gtxfifosizx {

04186                                                          is value derived from configuration parameters. */
04187     uint32_t txfdep                       : 16; /**< TxFIFOn depth. This value is in terms of TX RAM data width.
04188                                                          minimum value = 0x20, maximum value = 0x8000. */
04189 #else
04190     uint32_t txfdep                       : 16;
04191     uint32_t txfstaddr                    : 16;
04192 #endif

04199 /**
04200  * cvmx_uahc#_gtxthrcfg
04201  *
04202  * In a normal case, a TX burst starts as soon as one packet is prefetched. This works well as
04203  * long as the system bus is faster than the USB3.0 bus (a 1024-bytes packet takes ~2.2 us on the
04204  * USB bus in SuperSpeed mode). If the system bus latency is larger than 2.2 us to access a
04205  * 1024-byte packet, then starting a burst on 1-packet condition leads to an early abort of the
04206  * burst causing unnecessary performance reduction. This register allows the configuration of
04207  * threshold and burst size control. This feature is enabled by [USBTXPKTCNTSEL].
04208  *
04209  * Transmit path:
04210  * * The TX threshold is controlled by [USBTXPKTCNT], and the TX burst size is controlled by
04211  * [USBMAXTXBURSTSIZE].
04212  * * Selecting optimal TX FIFO size, TX threshold, and TX burst size avoids TX burst aborts due
04213  * to an underrun if the system bus is slower than USB. Once in a while an underrun is OK, and
04214  * there is no functional issue.
04215  * * A larger threshold affects the performance, since the scheduler is idle during this time.
04216  *
04217  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04218  */
04219 union cvmx_uahcx_gtxthrcfg {
04220     uint32_t u32;
04221     struct cvmx_uahcx_gtxthrcfg_s {
04222 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04223     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
04224     uint32_t usbtxpktcntsel               : 1;  /**< USB transmit packet-count enable. Enables/disables the USB transmission multipacket
04225                                                          thresholding:
04226                                                          0 = USB transmission multipacket thresholding is disabled, the core can only start
04227                                                          transmission on the USB after the entire packet has been fetched into the corresponding
04228                                                          TXFIFO.
04229                                                          1 = USB transmission multipacket thresholding is enabled. The core can only start
04230                                                          transmission on the USB after USBTXPKTCNT amount of packets for the USB transaction
04231                                                          (burst) are already in the corresponding TXFIFO.
04232                                                          This mode is only used for SuperSpeed. */
04233     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
04234     uint32_t usbtxpktcnt                  : 4;  /**< USB transmit-packet count. Specifies the number of packets that must be in the TXFIFO
04235                                                          before the core can start transmission for the corresponding USB transaction (burst). This
04236                                                          field is only valid when [USBTXPKTCNTSEL] = 1. Valid values are from 0x1 to 0xF.
04237                                                          This field must be <= [USBMAXTXBURSTSIZE]. */
04238     uint32_t usbmaxtxburstsize            : 8;  /**< USB maximum TX burst size. When [USBTXPKTCNTSEL] = 1, this field specifies the
04239                                                          maximum bulk OUT burst the core should do. When the system bus is slower than
04240                                                          the USB, TX FIFO can underrun during a long burst. Program a smaller value to
04241                                                          this field to limit the TX burst size that the core can do. It only applies to
04242                                                          SuperSpeed bulk, isochronous, and interrupt OUT endpoints in the host
04243                                                          mode. Valid values are from 0x1 to 0x10. */
04244     uint32_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
04245 #else
04246     uint32_t reserved_0_15                : 16;
04247     uint32_t usbmaxtxburstsize            : 8;
04248     uint32_t usbtxpktcnt                  : 4;
04249     uint32_t reserved_28_28               : 1;
04250     uint32_t usbtxpktcntsel               : 1;
04251     uint32_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
04252 #endif
04253     } s;
04254     struct cvmx_uahcx_gtxthrcfg_s         cn78xx;
04255     struct cvmx_uahcx_gtxthrcfg_s         cn78xxp1;
04256 };
04257 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_gtxthrcfg cvmx_uahcx_gtxthrcfg_t;

04259 /**
04260  * cvmx_uahc#_guctl
04261  *
04262  * This register provides a few options for the software to control the core behavior in the host
04263  * mode. Most of the options are used to improve host inter-operability with different devices.
04264  *
04265  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04266  */
04267 union cvmx_uahcx_guctl {
04268     uint32_t u32;
04269     struct cvmx_uahcx_guctl_s {
04270 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04271     uint32_t refclkper                    : 10; /**< Reference-clock period. Indicates (in terms of ns) the period of REF_CLK. The default
04272                                                          value is set to 0x8
04273                                                          (8 ns/125 MHz). This field must be updated during power on initialization if
04274                                                          UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1 or UAHC()_GFLADJ [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1. The
04275                                                          programmable maximum value 62 ns, and the minimum value is 8 ns. You use a reference clock
04276                                                          with a period that is a integer multiple, so that ITP can meet the jitter margin of 32 ns.
04277                                                          The allowable REF_CLK frequencies whose period is not integer multiples are
04278                                                          16/17/19.2/24/39.7 MHz.
04279                                                          This field should not be set to 0x0 at any time. If you do not plan to use this feature,
04280                                                          then you need to set this field to 0x8, the default value. */
04281     uint32_t noextrdl                     : 1;  /**< No extra delay between SOF and the first packet.
04282                                                          Some high-speed devices misbehave when the host sends a packet immediately after an SOF.
04283                                                          However, adding an extra delay between an SOF and the first packet can reduce the USB data
04284                                                          rate and performance.
04285                                                          This bit is used to control whether the host should wait for 2 us before it sends the
04286                                                          first packet after a SOF, or not. You can set this bit to 1 to improve the performance if
04287                                                          those problematic devices are not a concern in your host environment.
04288                                                          0 = host waits for 2 us after an SOF before it sends the first USB packet.
04289                                                          1 = host does not wait after an SOF before it sends the first USB packet. */
04290     uint32_t psqextrressp                 : 3;  /**< PSQ extra reserved space. This is a debug feature, and is not intended for normal usage.
04291                                                          This parameter specifies how much additional space in the PSQ (protocol-status queue) must
04292                                                          be reserved before the U3PTL initiates a new USB transaction and burst beats. */
04293     uint32_t sprsctrltransen              : 1;  /**< Sparse control transaction enable. Some devices are slow in responding to control
04294                                                          transfers. Scheduling multiple transactions in one microframe/frame can cause these
04295                                                          devices to misbehave. If this bit is set to 1, the host controller schedules transactions
04296                                                          for a control transfer in different microframes/frames. */
04297     uint32_t resbwhseps                   : 1;  /**< Reserving 85% bandwidth for high-speed periodic EPs. By default, host controller reserves
04298                                                          80% of the bandwidth for periodic EPs. If this bit is set, the bandwidth is relaxed to 85%
04299                                                          to accommodate two high-speed, high-bandwidth ISOC EPs.
04300                                                          USB 2.0 required 80% bandwidth allocated for ISOC traffic. If two high bandwidth ISOC
04301                                                          devices (HD webcams) are connected, and if each requires 1024-bytes * 3 packets per
04302                                                          microframe, then the bandwidth required is around 82%. If this bit is set to 1, it is
04303                                                          possible to connect two webcams of 1024 bytes * 3 payload per microframe each. Otherwise,
04304                                                          you may have to reduce the resolution of the webcams. */
04305     uint32_t cmdevaddr                    : 1;  /**< Compliance mode for device address. When set to 1, slot ID can have different value than
04306                                                          device address if max_slot_enabled < 128.
04307                                                          0 = Device address is equal to slot ID.
04308                                                          1 = Increment device address on each address device command.
04309                                                          The xHCI compliance requires this bit to be set to 1. The 0 mode is for debug purpose
04310                                                          only. This allows you to easily identify a device connected to a port in the Lecroy or
04311                                                          Eliisys trace during hardware debug. */
04312     uint32_t usbhstinautoretryen          : 1;  /**< Host IN auto-retry enable. When set, this field enables the auto-retry feature. For IN
04313                                                          transfers (non-isochronous) that encounter data packets with CRC errors or internal
04314                                                          overrun scenarios, the auto-retry feature causes the host core to reply to the device with
04315                                                          a non-terminating retry ACK (i.e. an ACK transaction packet with Retry = 1 and NumP != 0).
04316                                                          If the auto-retry feature is disabled (default), the core responds with a terminating
04317                                                          retry ACK (i.e. an ACK transaction packet with Retry = 1 and NumP = 0). */
04318     uint32_t enoverlapchk                 : 1;  /**< Enable check for LFPS overlap during remote Ux Exit. If this bit is set to:
04319                                                          0 = When the link exists U1/U2/U3 because of a remote exit, it does not look for an LFPS
04320                                                          overlap.
04321                                                          1 = The SuperSpeed link, when exiting U1/U2/U3, waits for either the remote link LFPS or
04322                                                          TS1/TS2 training symbols before it confirms that the LFPS handshake is complete. This is
04323                                                          done to handle the case where the LFPS glitch causes the link to start exiting from the
04324                                                          low power state. Looking for the LFPS overlap makes sure that the link partner also sees
04325                                                          the LFPS. */
04326     uint32_t extcapsupten                 : 1;  /**< External extended capability support enable. If disabled, a read UAHC()_SUPTPRT3_DW0
04327                                                          [NEXTCAPPTR] returns 0 in the next capability pointer field. This indicates there are no
04328                                                          more capabilities. If enabled, a read to UAHC()_SUPTPRT3_DW0[NEXTCAPPTR] returns 4 in the
04329                                                          next capability pointer field.
04330                                                          Always set to 0x0. */
04331     uint32_t insrtextrfsbodi              : 1;  /**< Insert extra delay between full-speed bulk OUT transactions. Some full-speed devices are
04332                                                          slow to receive bulk OUT data and can get stuck when there are consecutive bulk OUT
04333                                                          transactions with short inter-transaction delays. This bit is used to control whether the
04334                                                          host inserts extra delay between consecutive bulk OUT transactions to a full-speed
04335                                                          endpoint.
04336                                                          0 = Host does not insert extra delay.
04337                                                          Setting this bit to 1 reduces the bulk OUT transfer performance for most of the full-speed
04338                                                          devices.
04339                                                          1 = Host inserts about 12 us extra delay between consecutive bulk OUT transactions to an
04340                                                          full-speed endpoint to work around the device issue. */
04341     uint32_t dtct                         : 2;  /**< Device timeout coarse tuning. This field determines how long the host waits for a response
04342                                                          from device before considering a timeout.
04343                                                          The core first checks the [DTCT] value. If it is 0, then the timeout value is defined by
04344                                                          the
04345                                                          [DTFT]. If it is nonzero, then it uses the following timeout values:
04346                                                          0x0 = 0 us; use [DTFT] value instead.
04347                                                          0x1 = 500 us.
04348                                                          0x2 = 1.5 ms.
04349                                                          0x3 = 6.5 ms. */
04350     uint32_t dtft                         : 9;  /**< Device timeout fine tuning. This field determines how long the host waits for a response
04351                                                          from a device before considering a timeout. For [DTFT] to take effect, [DTCT] must be set
04352                                                          to
04353                                                          0x0.
04354                                                          The [DTFT] value specifies the number of 125 MHz clock cycles * 256 to count before
04355                                                          considering a device timeout. For the 125 MHz clock cycles (8 ns period), this is
04356                                                          calculated as follows:
04357                                                          _ [DTFT value] * 256 * 8 (ns)
04358                                                          0x2 = 2 * 256 * 8 -> 4 us.
04359                                                          0x5 = 5 * 256 * 8 -> 10 us.
04360                                                          0xA = 10 * 256 * 8 -> 20 us.
04361                                                          0x10 = 16 * 256 * 8 -> 32 us.
04362                                                          0x19 = 25 * 256 * 8 -> 51 us.
04363                                                          0x31 = 49 * 256 * 8 -> 100 us.
04364                                                          0x62 = 98 * 256 * 8 -> 200 us. */
04365 #else
04366     uint32_t dtft                         : 9;
04367     uint32_t dtct                         : 2;
04368     uint32_t insrtextrfsbodi              : 1;
04369     uint32_t extcapsupten                 : 1;
04370     uint32_t enoverlapchk                 : 1;
04371     uint32_t usbhstinautoretryen          : 1;
04372     uint32_t cmdevaddr                    : 1;
04373     uint32_t resbwhseps                   : 1;
04374     uint32_t sprsctrltransen              : 1;
04375     uint32_t psqextrressp                 : 3;
04376     uint32_t noextrdl                     : 1;
04377     uint32_t refclkper                    : 10;
04378 #endif
04379     } s;
04380     struct cvmx_uahcx_guctl_s             cn78xx;
04381     struct cvmx_uahcx_guctl_s             cn78xxp1;
04382 };
04383 typedef union cvmx_uahcx_guctl cvmx_uahcx_guctl_t;

04385 /**
04386  * cvmx_uahc#_guctl1
04387  *
04388  * This register can be reset by IOI reset or with UCTL()_CTL[UAHC_RST].
04389  *
04390  */
04391 union cvmx_uahcx_guctl1 {
04392     uint32_t u32;
04393     struct cvmx_uahcx_guctl1_s {
04394 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

04458 /**
04459  * cvmx_uahc#_gusb2phycfg#
04460  *
04461  * This register is used to configure the core after power-on. It contains USB 2.0 and USB 2.0
04462  * PHY-related configuration parameters. The application must program this register before
04463  * starting any transactions on either the SoC bus or the USB. Per-port registers are
04464  * implemented.
04465  *
04466  * Do not make changes to this register after the initial programming.
04467  */
04468 union cvmx_uahcx_gusb2phycfgx {
04469     uint32_t u32;
04470     struct cvmx_uahcx_gusb2phycfgx_s {
04471 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04472     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;  /**< PHY soft reset. Causes the usb2phy_reset signal to be asserted to reset a UTMI PHY. */
04473     uint32_t u2_freeclk_exists            : 1;  /**< Specifies whether your USB 2.0 PHY provides a free-running PHY clock, which is active when
04474                                                          the clock control input is active. If your USB 2.0 PHY provides a free-running PHY clock,
04475                                                          it must be connected to the utmi_clk[0] input. The remaining utmi_clk[n] must be connected
04476                                                          to the respective port clocks. The core uses the Port-0 clock for generating the internal
04477                                                          mac2 clock.
04478                                                          0 = USB 2.0 free clock does not exist.
04479                                                          1 = USB 2.0 free clock exists.
04480                                                          This field must be set to zero if you enable ITP generation based on the REF_CLK
04481                                                          counter, UAHC()_GCTL[SOFITPSYNC] = 1, or UAHC()_GFLADJ [GFLADJ_REFCLK_LPM_SEL] = 1. */
04482     uint32_t ulpi_lpm_with_opmode_chk     : 1;  /**< Support the LPM over ULPI without NOPID token to the ULPI PHY. Always 0x0. */
04483     uint32_t reserved_19_28               : 10;
04484     uint32_t ulpiextvbusindicator         : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04485     uint32_t ulpiextvbusdrv               : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04486     uint32_t ulpiclksusm                  : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04487     uint32_t ulpiautores                  : 1;  /**< Reserved (unused in this configuration). */
04488     uint32_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
04489     uint32_t usbtrdtim                    : 4;  /**< USB 2.0 turnaround time. Sets the turnaround time in PHY clock cycles. Specifies the
04490                                                          response time for a MAC request to the packet FIFO controller (PFC) to fetch data from the
04491                                                          DFIFO (SPRAM).
04492                                                          USB turnaround time is a critical certification criteria when using long cables and five
04493                                                          hub levels.
04494                                                          When the MAC interface is 8-bit UTMI+/ULPI, the required values for this field is 0x9. */
04495     uint32_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
04496     uint32_t enblslpm                     : 1;  /**< Enable utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n. The application uses this field to control
04497                                                          utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n assertion to the PHY in the L1 state.
04498                                                          0 = utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n assertion from the core is not transferred to the
04499                                                          external PHY.
04500                                                          1 = utmi_sleep_n and utmi_l1_suspend_n assertion from the core is transferred to the
04501                                                          external PHY.
04502                                                          When hardware LPM is enabled, this bit should be set high for Port0. */
04503     uint32_t physel                       : 1;  /**< USB 2.0 high-speed PHY or USB 1.1 full-speed serial transceiver select. */
04504     uint32_t susphy                       : 1;  /**< Suspend USB2.0 high-speed/full-speed/low-speed PHY. When set, USB2.0 PHY enters suspend
04505                                                          mode if suspend conditions are valid. */
04506     uint32_t fsintf                       : 1;  /**< Full-speed serial-interface select. Always reads as 0x0. */
04507     uint32_t ulpi_utmi_sel                : 1;  /**< ULPI or UTMI+ select. Always reads as 0x0, indicating UTMI+. */
04508     uint32_t phyif                        : 1;  /**< PHY interface width: 1 = 16-bit, 0 = 8-bit.
04509                                                          All the enabled 2.0 ports should have the same clock frequency as Port0 clock frequency
04510                                                          (utmi_clk[0]).
04511                                                          The UTMI 8-bit and 16-bit modes cannot be used together for different ports at the same
04512                                                          time (i.e., all the ports should be in 8-bit mode, or all of them should be in 16-bit
04513                                                          mode). */
04514     uint32_t toutcal                      : 3;  /**< High-speed/full-speed timeout calibration.
04515                                                          The number of PHY clock cycles, as indicated by the application in this field, is
04516                                                          multiplied by a bit-time factor; this factor is added to the high-speed/full-speed
04517                                                          interpacket timeout duration in the core to account for additional delays introduced by
04518                                                          the PHY. This might be required, since the delay introduced by the PHY in generating the
04519                                                          linestate condition can vary among PHYs.
04520                                                          The USB standard timeout value for high-speed operation is 736 to 816 (inclusive) bit
04521                                                          times. The USB standard timeout value for full-speed operation is 16 to 18 (inclusive) bit
04522                                                          times. The application must program this field based on the speed of connection.
04523                                                          The number of bit times added per PHY clock are:
04524                                                          * High-speed operation:
04525                                                          _ one 30-MHz PHY clock = 16 bit times.
04526                                                          _ one 60-MHz PHY clock = 8 bit times.
04527                                                          * Full-speed operation:
04528                                                          _ one 30-MHz PHY clock = 0.4 bit times.
04529                                                          _ one 60-MHz PHY clock = 0.2 bit times.
04530                                                          _ one 48-MHz PHY clock = 0.25 bit times. */
04531 #else
04532     uint32_t toutcal                      : 3;
04533     uint32_t phyif                        : 1;
04534     uint32_t ulpi_utmi_sel                : 1;
04535     uint32_t fsintf                       : 1;
04536     uint32_t susphy                       : 1;
04537     uint32_t physel                       : 1;
04538     uint32_t enblslpm                     : 1;
04539     uint32_t reserved_9_9                 : 1;
04540     uint32_t usbtrdtim                    : 4;
04541     uint32_t reserved_14_14               : 1;
04542     uint32_t ulpiautores                  : 1;
04543     uint32_t ulpiclksusm                  : 1;
04544     uint32_t ulpiextvbusdrv               : 1;
04545     uint32_t ulpiextvbusindicator         : 1;
04546     uint32_t reserved_19_28               : 10;
04547     uint32_t ulpi_lpm_with_opmode_chk     : 1;
04548     uint32_t u2_freeclk_exists            : 1;
04549     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;
04550 #endif
04551     } s;
04552     struct cvmx_uahcx_gusb2phycfgx_s      cn78xx;
04553     struct cvmx_uahcx_gusb2phycfgx_s      cn78xxp1;

04557 /**
04558  * cvmx_uahc#_gusb3pipectl#
04559  *
04560  * This register is used to configure the core after power-on. It contains USB 3.0 and USB 3.0
04561  * PHY-related configuration parameters. The application must program this register before
04562  * starting any transactions on either the SoC bus or the USB. Per-port registers are
04563  * implemented.
04564  *
04565  * Do not make changes to this register after the initial programming.
04566  */
04567 union cvmx_uahcx_gusb3pipectlx {
04568     uint32_t u32;
04569     struct cvmx_uahcx_gusb3pipectlx_s {
04570 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04571     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;  /**< USB3 PHY soft reset (PHYSoftRst). When set to 1, initiates a PHY soft reset. After setting
04572                                                          this bit to 1, the software needs to clear this bit. */
04573     uint32_t hstprtcmpl                   : 1;  /**< Host port compliance. Setting this bit to 1 enables placing the SuperSpeed port link into
04574                                                          a compliance state, which allows testing of the PIPE PHY compliance patterns without
04575                                                          having to have a test fixture on the USB 3.0 cable. By default, this bit should be set to
04576                                                          0.
04577                                                          In compliance-lab testing, the SuperSpeed port link enters compliance after failing the
04578                                                          first polling sequence after power on. Set this bit to 0 when you run compliance tests.
04579                                                          The sequence for using this functionality is as follows:
04580                                                          * Disconnect any plugged-in devices.
04581                                                          * Set UAHC()_USBCMD[HCRST] = 1 or power-on-chip reset.
04582                                                          * Set UAHC()_PORTSC()[PP] = 0.
04583                                                          * Set HSTPRTCMPL = 1. This places the link into compliance state.
04584                                                          To advance the compliance pattern, follow this sequence (toggle HSTPRTCMPL):
04585                                                          * Set HSTPRTCMPL = 0.
04586                                                          * Set HSTPRTCMPL = 1. This advances the link to the next compliance pattern.
04587                                                          To exit from the compliance state, set UAHC()_USBCMD[HCRST] = 1 or power-on-chip reset. */
04588     uint32_t u2ssinactp3ok                : 1;  /**< P3 OK for U2/SS.Inactive:
04589                                                          0 = During link state U2/SS.Inactive, put PHY in P2 (default).
04590                                                          1 = During link state U2/SS.Inactive, put PHY in P3. */
04591     uint32_t disrxdetp3                   : 1;  /**< Disables receiver detection in P3. If PHY is in P3 and the core needs to perform receiver
04592                                                          detection:
04593                                                          0 = Core performs receiver detection in P3 (default).
04594                                                          1 = Core changes the PHY power state to P2 and then performs receiver detection. After
04595                                                          receiver detection, core changes PHY power state to P3. */
04596     uint32_t ux_exit_in_px                : 1;  /**< UX exit in Px:
04597                                                          0 = Core does U1/U2/U3 exit in PHY power state P0 (default behavior).
04598                                                          1 = Core does U1/U2/U3 exit in PHY power state P1/P2/P3 respectively.
04599                                                          This bit is added for SuperSpeed PHY workaround where SuperSpeed PHY injects a glitch on
04600                                                          pipe3_RxElecIdle while receiving Ux exit LFPS, and pipe3_PowerDown change is in progress. */
04601     uint32_t ping_enchance_en             : 1;  /**< Ping enhancement enable. When set to 1, the downstream-port U1-ping-receive timeout
04602                                                          becomes 500 ms instead of 300 ms. Minimum Ping.LFPS receive duration is 8 ns (one mac3_clk
04603                                                          cycle). This field is valid for the downstream port only. */
04604     uint32_t u1u2exitfail_to_recov        : 1;  /**< U1U2exit fail to recovery. When set to 1, and U1/U2 LFPS handshake fails, the LTSSM
04605                                                          transitions from U1/U2 to recovery instead of SS.inactive.
04606                                                          If recovery fails, then the LTSSM can enter SS.Inactive. This is an enhancement only. It
04607                                                          prevents interoperability issue if the remote link does not do the proper handshake. */
04608     uint32_t request_p1p2p3               : 1;  /**< Always request P1/P2/P3 for U1/U2/U3.
04609                                                          0 = if immediate Ux exit (remotely initiated, or locally initiated) happens, the core does
04610                                                          not request P1/P2/P3 power state change.
04611                                                          1 = the core always requests PHY power change from P0 to P1/P2/P3 during U0 to U1/U2/U3
04612                                                          transition. */
04613     uint32_t startrxdetu3rxdet            : 1;  /**< Start receiver detection in U3/Rx.Detect.
04614                                                          If DISRXDETU3RXDET is set to 1 during reset, and the link is in U3 or Rx.Detect state, the
04615                                                          core starts receiver detection on rising edge of this bit.
04616                                                          This bit is valid for downstream ports only, and this feature must not be enabled for
04617                                                          normal operation. */
04618     uint32_t disrxdetu3rxdet              : 1;  /**< Disable receiver detection in U3/Rx.Detect. When set to 1, the core does not do receiver
04619                                                          detection in U3 or Rx.Detect state. If STARTRXDETU3RXDET is set to 1 during reset,
04620                                                          receiver detection starts manually.
04621                                                          This bit is valid for downstream ports only, and this feature must not be enabled for
04622                                                          normal operation. */
04623     uint32_t delaypx                      : 3;  /**< Delay P1P2P3. Delay P0 to P1/P2/P3 request when entering U1/U2/U3 until (DELAYPX * 8)
04624                                                          8B10B error occurs, or Pipe3_RxValid drops to 0.
04625                                                          DELAYPXTRANSENTERUX must reset to 1 to enable this functionality. */
04626     uint32_t delaypxtransenterux          : 1;  /**< Delay PHY power change from P0 to P1/P2/P3 when link state changing from U0 to U1/U2/U3
04627                                                          respectively.
04628                                                          0 = when entering U1/U2/U3, transition to P1/P2/P3 without checking for Pipe3_RxElecIlde
04629                                                          and pipe3_RxValid.
04630                                                          1 = when entering U1/U2/U3, delay the transition to P1/P2/P3 until the pipe3 signals,
04631                                                          Pipe3_RxElecIlde is 1 and pipe3_RxValid is 0. */
04632     uint32_t suspend_en                   : 1;  /**< Suspend USB3.0 SuperSpeed PHY (Suspend_en). When set to 1, and if suspend conditions are
04633                                                          valid, the USB 3.0 PHY enters suspend mode. */
04634     uint32_t datwidth                     : 2;  /**< PIPE data width.
04635                                                          0x0 = 32 bits.
04636                                                          0x1 = 16 bits.
04637                                                          0x2 = 8 bits.
04638                                                          0x3 = reserved.
04639                                                          One clock cycle after reset, these bits receive the value seen on the pipe3_DataBusWidth.
04640                                                          This will always be 0x0. */
04641     uint32_t abortrxdetinu2               : 1;  /**< Abort RX Detect in U2. When set to 1, and the link state is U2, the core aborts receiver
04642                                                          detection if it receives U2 exit LFPS from the remote link partner.
04643                                                          This bit is for downstream port only. */
04644     uint32_t skiprxdet                    : 1;  /**< Skip RX detect. When set to 1, the core skips RX detection if pipe3_RxElecIdle is low.
04645                                                          Skip is defined as waiting for the appropriate timeout, then repeating the operation. */
04646     uint32_t lfpsp0algn                   : 1;  /**< LFPS P0 align. When set to 1:
04647                                                          * the core deasserts LFPS transmission on the clock edge that it requests Phy power state
04648                                                          0 when exiting U1, U2, or U3 low power states. Otherwise, LFPS transmission is asserted
04649                                                          one clock earlier.
04650                                                          * the core requests symbol transmission two pipe3_rx_pclks periods after the PHY asserts
04651                                                          PhyStatus as a result of the PHY switching from P1 or P2 state to P0 state.
04652                                                          For USB 3.0 host, this is not required. */
04653     uint32_t p3p2tranok                   : 1;  /**< P3 P2 transitions OK.
04654                                                          0 = P0 is always entered as an intermediate state during transitions between P2 and P3, as
04655                                                          defined in the PIPE3 specification.
04656                                                          1 = the core transitions directly from Phy power state P2 to P3 or from state P3 to P2.
04657                                                          According to PIPE3 specification, any direct transition between P3 and P2 is illegal. */
04658     uint32_t p3exsigp2                    : 1;  /**< P3 exit signal in P2. When set to 1, the core always changes the PHY power state to P2,
04659                                                          before attempting a U3 exit handshake. */
04660     uint32_t lfpsfilt                     : 1;  /**< LFPS filter. When set to 1, filter LFPS reception with pipe3_RxValid in PHY power state
04661                                                          P0, ignore LFPS reception from the PHY unless both pipe3_Rxelecidle and pipe3_RxValid are
04662                                                          deasserted. */
04663     uint32_t rxdet2polllfpsctrl           : 1;  /**< RX_DETECT to Polling.
04664                                                          0 = Enables a 400 us delay to start polling LFPS after RX_DETECT. This allows VCM offset
04665                                                          to settle to a proper level.
04666                                                          1 = Disables the 400 us delay to start polling LFPS after RX_DETECT. */
04667     uint32_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
04668     uint32_t txswing                      : 1;  /**< TX swing. Refer to the PIPE3 specification. */
04669     uint32_t txmargin                     : 3;  /**< TX margin. Refer to the PIPE3 specification, table 5-3. */
04670     uint32_t txdeemphasis                 : 2;  /**< TX deemphasis. The value driven to the PHY is controlled by the LTSSM during USB3
04671                                                          compliance mode. Refer to the PIPE3 specification, table 5-3.
04672                                                          Use the following values for the appropriate level of de-emphasis (From pipe3 spec):
04673                                                          0x0 =   -6 dB de-emphasis, use UCTL()_PORT()_CFG_SS[PCS_TX_DEEMPH_6DB].
04674                                                          0x1 = -3.5 dB de-emphasis, use UCTL()_PORT()_CFG_SS[PCS_TX_DEEMPH_3P5DB].
04675                                                          0x2 =     No de-emphasis.
04676                                                          0x3 =     Reserved. */
04677     uint32_t elasticbuffermode            : 1;  /**< Elastic buffer mode. Refer to the PIPE3 specification, table 5-3. */
04678 #else
04679     uint32_t elasticbuffermode            : 1;
04680     uint32_t txdeemphasis                 : 2;
04681     uint32_t txmargin                     : 3;
04682     uint32_t txswing                      : 1;
04683     uint32_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
04684     uint32_t rxdet2polllfpsctrl           : 1;
04685     uint32_t lfpsfilt                     : 1;
04686     uint32_t p3exsigp2                    : 1;
04687     uint32_t p3p2tranok                   : 1;
04688     uint32_t lfpsp0algn                   : 1;
04689     uint32_t skiprxdet                    : 1;
04690     uint32_t abortrxdetinu2               : 1;
04691     uint32_t datwidth                     : 2;
04692     uint32_t suspend_en                   : 1;
04693     uint32_t delaypxtransenterux          : 1;
04694     uint32_t delaypx                      : 3;
04695     uint32_t disrxdetu3rxdet              : 1;
04696     uint32_t startrxdetu3rxdet            : 1;
04697     uint32_t request_p1p2p3               : 1;
04698     uint32_t u1u2exitfail_to_recov        : 1;
04699     uint32_t ping_enchance_en             : 1;
04700     uint32_t ux_exit_in_px                : 1;
04701     uint32_t disrxdetp3                   : 1;
04702     uint32_t u2ssinactp3ok                : 1;
04703     uint32_t hstprtcmpl                   : 1;
04704     uint32_t physoftrst                   : 1;
04705 #endif
04706     } s;
04707     struct cvmx_uahcx_gusb3pipectlx_s     cn78xx;
04708     struct cvmx_uahcx_gusb3pipectlx_s     cn78xxp1;
04709 };

04914 /**
04915  * cvmx_uahc#_ohci0_hcbulkcurrented
04916  *
04917  * HCBULKCURRENTED = Host Controller Bulk Current ED Register
04918  *
04919  * The HcBulkCurrentED register contains the physical address of the current endpoint of the Bulk list. As the Bulk list will be served in a round-robin
04920  * fashion, the endpoints will be ordered according to their insertion to the list.
04921  */

04926     uint32_t bced                         : 28; /**< BulkCurrentED. This is advanced to the next ED after the HC has served the
04927                                                          present one. HC continues processing the list from where it left off in the
04928                                                          last Frame. When it reaches the end of the Bulk list, HC checks the
04929                                                          ControlListFilled of HcControl. If set, it copies the content of HcBulkHeadED
04930                                                          to HcBulkCurrentED and clears the bit. If it is not set, it does nothing.
04931                                                          HCD is only allowed to modify this register when the BulkListEnable of
04932                                                          HcControl is cleared. When set, the HCD only reads the instantaneous value of
04933                                                          this register. This is initially set to zero to indicate the end of the Bulk
04934                                                          list. */
04935     uint32_t reserved_0_3                 : 4;
04936 #else
04937     uint32_t reserved_0_3                 : 4;
04938     uint32_t bced                         : 28;
04939 #endif
04940     } s;
04941     struct cvmx_uahcx_ohci0_hcbulkcurrented_s cn61xx;
04942     struct cvmx_uahcx_ohci0_hcbulkcurrented_s cn63xx;
